{"TopicId":156997,"ForumId":51,"TopicTitle":"DAMTS - Direct Ascent Munar Transport System","CreatedByName":"MedwedianPresident","CreatedById":12212,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-26T10:16:00Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"MedwedianPresident","CreatedById":12212,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-26T10:16:00Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:center;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan style=\u0022font-size:26px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDIRECT ASCENT MUNAR TRANSPORT SYSTEM\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan style=\u0022font-size:12px;\u0022\u003EThe\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003ED\u003C/strong\u003Eirect\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003EA\u003C/strong\u003Escent\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003EM\u003C/strong\u003Eunar\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003ET\u003C/strong\u003Eransport\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003ES\u003C/strong\u003Eystem is a versatile framework for situations in which every minute counts such as rescues of stranded or crashed kerbonauts. Inspired by the Apollo Direct Ascent and the Gemini Lunar Lander hypothetical designs, the DAMTS brings up to 3 crewmen (by default) to the Mun within 6 hours. Sitting atop the massive Supernova rocket which utilizes SpaceY 7.5m and 10m parts, the DAMTS can be outfitted with various functional modules (which serve as the descent stage of the\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003EH\u003C/strong\u003Eeavy\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003EM\u003C/strong\u003Eunar\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003EL\u003C/strong\u003Eander (HML)) that remain on the Mun and are capable of making ballistic hops or entering Munar orbit for docking with a station.\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nLaunch wet mass is almost 4000 tons.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u00226EO6qbQ.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/6EO6qbQ.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe initial \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Thrust-to-weight ratio\u0022\u003ETWR\u003C/abbr\u003E is relatively low.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u002262k2owX.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/62k2owX.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nGravity turn is relatively shallow. Main engine thrust is gradually lowered and then increased to full again when boosters are separated. This saves fuel.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022CH6atui.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/CH6atui.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe boosters tend to explode upon separation; however, they do not damage the rocket (usually).\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022cHukp8L.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/cHukp8L.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nSix ullage motors kick the first stage away. The \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Launch Escape System\u0022\u003ELES\u003C/abbr\u003E has already been jettisoned by now.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022k7g0UJl.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/k7g0UJl.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe second stage is over-engineered. It does not only circularize, but also performs the TMI burn and insertion into Munar orbit.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022ZTx0x46.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/ZTx0x46.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe Mun is reachable within several hours.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022uPiTIZ8.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/uPiTIZ8.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nAfter Munar Orbit Insertion, the 2nd stage is jettisoned using four ullage motors. This shows that the rocket is designed for larger payloads - the 3rd stage is supposed to function as the transfer stage.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022LofRdph.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/LofRdph.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe HML is a relatively light payload; as such, the third stage controls the first half of the descent.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022sMMOPRx.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/sMMOPRx.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nOnce it has been determined that the landing must not be aborted, the third stage is separated and the Descent Stage of the HML ignited. Note the eight shallow landing legs which stabilize the lander and allow it to land in sloped terrain without tipping over.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022Uo7pwVf.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/Uo7pwVf.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe HML, as any other Munar landers, requires advanced piloting skills. Thrust must be modulated appropriately - if piloted incorrectly, the lander crashes.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022xJladFT.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/xJladFT.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nIn this case, the HML landed on a ~5deg slope. It slowly skidded down as the Jeb, Bill and Bob posed for a picture.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022f7rwvop.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/f7rwvop.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003EMU\u003C/strong\u003Enar\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003ERE\u003C/strong\u003Esource\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003Extraction\u00A0\u003Cstrong\u003EM\u003C/strong\u003Eodule (MUREM) slowly mines for Munar ore. It can be used for supplying small bases.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u00221FAhCfx.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/1FAhCfx.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe small engine of the Ascent and Return Stage does not damage the Descent Stage with its exhaust.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u00224gToTyf.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/4gToTyf.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe Ascent and Return Stage steadily rises into Low Munar Orbit.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022toCM6CQ.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/toCM6CQ.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe ARS brings\u00A0the vessel into a Kerbin Return and Reentry trajectory (periapsis ~20-30k); some fuel is left for course corrections.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022rEhaKuH.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/rEhaKuH.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nNote the \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003ERCS\u003C/abbr\u003E ports located on the CM - their purpose is translation to clear the ADS after separation and prevent a collision during Reentry.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022Truf0XX.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/Truf0XX.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\nThe entry velocity (3000 m/s) is typical for returning from the Mun.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022text-align:justify;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022toHeO3v.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 height=\u0022562\u0022 src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/toHeO3v.png\u0022 width=\u00221000\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}